FastAPI -> python based web framework
scarlet -> build in top of starlet for the web parts
pydantic -> data part

React -> pjavascript library for building user interfaces

mongodb -> document oriented no sql database stores data in flexible json like documents ; meaning datastructes can be changed overtime

FastAPI ->
pip install "fastapi[standard]"
-> install

pip install "fastapi[all]"
from typing import union 

code ->
app = FastAPI()
✔️ Creates your FastAPI application
✔️ Used to define all API endpoints
✔️ Uvicorn runs this object

@app.get("/")
4 examples
@ → decorator symbol.
app → FastAPI application instance.
get → HTTP method for retrieval.
"/" → root URL path

/items/10
Returns:
{
  "item_id": 10,
  "q": null
}
/items/10?q=phone
Returns:
{
  "item_id": 10,
  "q": "phone"
}

the ? marks seperates the items value and q value ->
? : is how the urls work, it is standard format.
/items/30?q=20p
{
  "item_id": 30,
  "q": "20p"
}

(/path?query#fragment)

we run the server using uvicorn server -> pip install uvicorn
FastAPI is built on ASGI (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface).
Uvicorn is an ASGI server.
Both are fully async → extremely fast.

-> uvicorn main:app --reload

when opened in the server ->
http://127.0.0.1:8000/items -> hello : world
http://127.0.0.1:8000/items/6?q=letsgo -> 

| URL                    | FastAPI `q` value |
| ---------------------- | ----------------- |
| `/items/6?q=letsgo`    | `"letsgo"`        |
| `/items/6?q=lets%20go` | `"lets go"`       |
| `/items/6?q=lets+go`   | `"lets go"`       |

http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs -> shows the documentation of the api
http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc -> different way to show the documentation of the api


put request ->
from pydantic import BaseModel

class Item(baseModel):
  name : str
  price : float
  is_offer : Union[bool,None] = None

@app.put("/items/{item_id}")
def update_item(item_id :int ,item: Item):
  return {"item_name" : item.name, "item_id" : item_id}

Get v/s Put request :
| Feature    | GET                      | PUT                    |
| ---------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------- |
| Purpose    | Read data                | Update/create data     |
| Body       | ❌ usually empty          | ✔ contains data (JSON) |
| Idempotent | ✔                        | ✔                      |
| Cacheable  | ✔                        | ❌                      |
| Safety     | ✔ Does not modify server | ❌ Modifies server      |
| Example    | Get item info            | Update item info       |

Client sends this JSON:
{
  "name": "Pen",
  "price": 10.5,
  "is_offer": true
}

FastAPI parses it into an Item object: 
item.name      # "Pen"
item.price     # 10.5
item.is_offer  # True

PUT request (@app.put)
PUT is an HTTP method used to update data on the server.
The URL path /items/{item_id} identifies which resource to update.
The request body contains the new data to update.













